<TITLE> UN praises Dhaka's anti-terrorism stance, offers help </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 30 (bdnews24.com)The United Nations has hailed Bangladesh's tough stand against terrorism and offered all possible assistance in Dhaka's efforts to curb extremism, according to the foreign ministry. The praise came when chief of the UN Security Council's Counter Terrorism Committee Mike Smith meet with foreign minister Dipu Moni at her hotel suite on Tuesday afternoon in New York . "The Counter Terrorism Committee hailed the strong stance of the current government against terrorism and extremism and assured the minister of every cooperation in this regard," said a press statement issued on Wednesday. The foreign minister highlighted the steps taken by the government to counter the menace of terrorism, including promulgation of Anti Terrorism Ordinance, 2008 and Anti Money Laundering Ordinance, 2008, the statement said. Earlier, Richard O Blake, US assistant secretary of state, Bureau for South and Central Asian Affairs, called on Moni at her suite. "Their discussion was focused on addressing the issues of climate change, food security and counter-terrorism. The two leaders then discussed how terrorism was snatching the necessary resources away from the world's development endeavors," the statement said. "Dipu Moni, in this vein, highlighted the importance to find out easier ways and means for the extradition of the convicted peoples in either direction," it said. Foreign secretary Mohamed Mijarul Quayes was also present during the meeting. Moni is now on a tour of US.
